scheduled_maintenances.name: Scheduled Zoom Software Quarterly Lifecycle update (2/4/23)

incident_updates.body:
As a reminder 30 days ahead of the upcoming enforcement, Zoom will be enforcing a new global minimum version for all our Zoom clients and plugins this February 4th, 2023. This affects the following products:
- Zoom client for meetings (Windows, macOS, Linux, iOS, Android, Blackberry, and Intune)
- Zoom Rooms*
- Zoom Phone Appliances
- VDI Client 
- Virtual Room Connector
- Meetings Connector
- Recording Connector
- Meeting SDK (native and web)
- Video SDK (native and web)

*Note: Zoom Room Controllers will not be enforced with this enforcement. 

For more information, such as specific versions we are enforcing, refer to the Zoom Software Quarterly Lifecycle Policy support article: https://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/360059429231

To assist with checking the client versions on your account, refer to the Dashboard support article: https://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/360039656511#h_13ce9a73-91e5-4df6-9cb5-c815b1605cf5

Zoom will be enforcing a new minimum version of all our Zoom clients and plugins, roughly 90 days from now on February 4th, 2023. This affects the following products: 
- Zoom client for meetings (Windows, macOS, Linux, iOS, Android, Blackberry, and Intune)
- Zoom Rooms (including Zoom Room Controllers) 
- Zoom Phone Appliances
- VDI Client and Plugin
- Virtual Room Connector
- Meetings Connector
- Recording Connector
- Meetings SDK (Native and Web)
- Video SDK (Native and Web)

Please ensure your devices are updated to the latest version. 

For more information, such as specific versions we are enforcing, please see the Zoom Software Quarterly Lifecycle Policy support article: https://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/360059429231 

To assist with checking the client versions on your account, refer to the Dashboard support article for more information: https://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/360039656511#h_13ce9a73-91e5-4df6-9cb5-c815b1605cf5

Zoom Phone users registered to the Tokyo data center will be automatically registered in an alternative datacenter starting at 12:00PM GMT Time (4:00AM Pacific) on February 4th. During the maintenance window, a brief disconnection may be experienced and notifications may be missed. If you get disconnected, the system will attempt to reconnect you automatically. If you are a BYOC (Bring Your Own Carrier) customer, please ensure that your Session Border Controller (SBC) is configured with alternate routing to Zooms Osaka data center in addition to the Tokyo data center. During the maintenance window, connectivity to Zooms Tokyo data center will be blocked which will force calls from the Session Border Controller (SBC) to failover to Zooms Osaka data center. Traffic will continue to be routed through the Zoom Tokyo data center once the maintenance is completed.

For customers that use hardware phones, refer to this link for the devices support the alternative datacenter process as described above: https://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/360029698771#h_01GNZ783VT6YXHES8NSXBA5M9A
We will be undergoing scheduled maintenance during this time.

affected_components.name: NORTH AMERICAS - Zoom Phone - Zoom Phone

incident_updates.body:
We will be performing maintenance on our Denver datacenter (DV) on February 10th, 2023 9PM Mountain Time through February 12th, 2023 6AM Mountain Time.

No new meetings will be started in the Denver datacenter (DV) after 9AM Mountain Time on February 11th. However, if any meetings started in the Denver datacenter (DV) are still ongoing at 9AM Mountain Time on February 11th, they will be ended and can be manually restarted in another datacenter.

Zoom Phone and Zoom Contact Center users registered to the Denver datacenter (DV) will be automatically registered in an alternative datacenter starting at 9PM Mountain Time on February 10th. During the maintenance window, a brief disconnection may be experienced and notifications may be missed. If you get disconnected, the system will attempt to reconnect you automatically. If you are a BYOC (Bring Your Own Carrier) customer, please ensure that your Session Border Controller (SBC) is configured with alternate routing to the San Jose (SJ) and New York (NY) data center in addition to the Denver datacenter (DV). During the maintenance window, connectivity to the Denver datacenter (DV) will be blocked, which will force calls from the Session Border Controller (SBC) to failover to the San Jose (SJ) data center and New York (NY) data center. Traffic will continue to be routed through the Denver datacenter (DV) once the maintenance is completed.

For customers that use hardware phones, refer to this link for the devices support the alternative datacenter process as described above: https://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/360029698771-Supported-desk-phone-features#h_01GNZ783VT6YXHES8NSXBA5M9A

scheduled_maintenances.name: Announcing IP Address Changes (No Operational Impact)

incident_updates.body:
The following, new and updated IP subnet ranges will be deployed to Zoom Phone resources starting no earlier than 30 days from the posting of this notice.
New IP address ranges:
121.244.146.0/27
203.200.219.128/27

Additionally, Zoom will be adding additional data centers as a part of the global Zoom routing network. These sites are already in our previously announced IP address ranges and will be enabled at launch for customers. For network administrators with Zoom specific proxy rules, please update your PAC files with the following sites to utilize these data centers.

New data centers:
Vancouver - yvr.zoom.us 
Toronto - yyz.zoom.us
Mexico - qro.zoom.us
Sydney - syd.zoom.us
Melbourne - mel.zoom.us
Osaka - kix.zoom.us
Mumbai - bom.zoom.us 
Hyderabad - hyd.zoom.us

A complete list of network firewall IP ranges for Zoom can be found on the Zoom Support site at: https://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/201362683
